#v(0.4fr)

Naturalistic programming is broadly defined as the attempt to write computer code in a varyingly complex subset of natural language. This work explores how existing naturalistic programming languages try to bring program specifications a little bit closer to the way humans naturally describe things and processes, relating it to the broad topic of "Common Sense" in Artificial Intelligence. Moreover, the thesis proposes a new prototype of rule-based naturalistic language, which follows the principles of the languages surveyed, but also introduces a notion of _automated planning_ to facilitate declarative programming.

